114 cm3 Ge(Li) detector (efficiency 30%)
Energy uncertainty includes those of target
thickness and beam energy resolution
Uncertainties due to target-foil thickness
Uncertainties due to the beam current
integration
Uncertainties due to the detector efficiency
The uncertainties caused by the large size of
the irradiation area and the non uniformities of the
target contribute about 5% to the average error of the
cross section
Uncertainties due to the analysis of
the gamma-ray spectra (statistical uncertainty)
Cross-section uncertainties includes
all sources mentioned above.
However, these uncertainties do not include the
uncertainties of the nuclear data used in the analysis

measurements of Al-27(alpha,x) reaction
Fusion cross
sections deduced from excitation functions.
The targets were obtained by vacuum evaporation of the
gallium nitrate for Ga and antimony trioxide for Sb
targets on 23.4 um thick Al backings (30 mm in diam.)
placed over the masking plate. In the masking plate
there were 16 open circles of 20 mm in diam. In one
evaporation 16 targets were prepared. The thickness
of the targets obtained after the evaporation was
about 1.0 mg/cm2 for Ga and 2 mg/cm2 for antimony.
Aluminum target backings were 23.4 um thick and
degraders were 23.4 or 4.34 um thick.
Since the radionuclides As-71 and As-72 could also
produced via (a,4n) and (a,3n) reactions on Ga-71,
respectively, in the overlapping region these cross
sections are taken proportional to the theoretical
values based on the hybrid model of M.Blann, University
of Rochester Report No. Coo-3494-29.
